### Tool 1.2 — Abstraction Quality Scorer
**Source:** Pattern 2 (Abstraction at the Rate-Distortion Knee)

**What it does:** Given a source representation and an abstracted representation of the same underlying phenomenon, estimates where the abstraction falls on the rate-distortion curve and scores whether it's near the knee (good abstraction), too compressed (lossy), or insufficiently compressed (cluttered).

**Inputs:**
- Paired source/target representations (text summaries vs. source material; schematic vs. detailed diagram; mathematical model vs. raw data)
- A distortion metric $d$ appropriate to the domain (semantic distance, pixel-wise error, functional divergence)

**Outputs:**
- Position on the rate-distortion curve
- "Sharpness" $\alpha$ score (curvature at the operating point)
- Qualitative verdict: reductive / optimal / cluttered

**Buildable with:** Modern embedding models (for text/images) provide the distortion metric. The rate-distortion curve can be estimated empirically by computing $I(X; \hat{X})$ and $\mathbb{E}[d(X, \hat{X})]$ across a range of compression levels using information-theoretic estimators (e.g., k-nearest-neighbor MI estimators from Kraskov et al. 2004).

